"\n|63\n|[https://vmestates.com/wp-content/uploads/phases/b3/c2/38/3aefdca24ff74862a22a21e495b9e299/3aefdca24ff74862a22a21e495b9e299.jpg '''180\u00b0 Limassol''']\n|[[Limassol]]\n|\u224856m\n|\u2248184ft\n|14\n|2021\n|Under Construction\n|Residential\n|<small>Concrete foundations poured. Now climbing above ground level<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://vmestates.com/project/180-limassol-residence/666a7d56-b01a-4120-8c30-ab56bdef832a|title=180\u00b0 Limassol Residence|website=VM Estates|language=en-US|access-date=2020-01-28}}</ref></small>\n|-\n|- style=\"background: pink;\"\n|64\n|[https://scontent.fath4-2.fna.fbcdn.net/v/t1.0-9/p960x960/86170196_825710434573375_4306155436697976832_o.jpg?_nc_cat=108&_nc_ohc=CUqLdvp5TWUAX8-XrHW&_nc_ht=scontent.fath4-2.fna&_nc_tp=6&oh=20b2fdcdf65fcedc5624046d836dfefe&oe=5EFF8630 '''Central'''] <small>Block A</small>\n|[[Nicosia]]\n|55,3m\n|181,5ft\n|15\n|\n|Proposed\n|Commercial\n|<small><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.stockwatch.com.cy/el/article/ktimatagorakataskeyes/dyo-nea-polyorofa-ktiria-me-grafeia-apo-cyfield|title=\u0394\u03cd\u03bf \u03bd\u03ad\u03b1 \u03c0\u03bf\u03bb\u03c5\u03ce\u03c1\u03bf\u03c6\u03b1 \u03ba\u03c4\u03ae\u03c1\u03b9\u03b1 \u03bc\u03b5 \u03b3\u03c1\u03b1\u03c6\u03b5\u03af\u03b1 \u03b1\u03c0\u03cc Cyfield|date=2020-02-13|website=Stockwatch - \u03a0\u03b1\u03c1\u03ac\u03b8\u03c5\u03c1\u03bf \u03c3\u03c4\u03b7\u03bd \u039f\u03b9\u03ba\u03bf\u03bd\u03bf\u03bc\u03af\u03b1|language=el|access-date=2020-02-14}}</ref></small>\n|-\n|- style=\"background: pink;\"\n|65\n|[https://www.philenews.com/temp/images/728x3000/cache_728x3000_Analog_medium_891155_140315_632020_the-gallery.JPG '''The Gallery''']\n|[[Limassol]]\n|54,2m\n|177,8ft\n|10\n|\n|Proposed\n|Mixed Use\n|<small><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://inbusinessnews.reporter.com.cy/business/property/article/241380/nea-oikistiki-kai-emporiki-anaptyxi-ston-paraliako-tis-lemesoy|title=\u039d\u03ad\u03b1 \u03bf\u03b9\u03ba\u03b9\u03c3\u03c4\u03b9\u03ba\u03ae \u03ba\u03b1\u03b9 \u03b5\u03bc\u03c0\u03bf\u03c1\u03b9\u03ba\u03ae \u03b1\u03bd\u03ac\u03c0\u03c4\u03c5\u03be\u03b7 \u03c3\u03c4\u03bf\u03bd \u03c0\u03b1\u03c1\u03b1\u03bb\u03b9\u03b1\u03ba\u03cc \u03c4\u03b7\u03c2 \u039b\u03b5\u03bc\u03b5\u03c3\u03bf\u03cd|website=InBusiness|access-date=2020-03-06}}</ref></small>\n|- style=\"background:#87CEFA;\"\n|66\n|[https://cdn.shortpixel.ai/client/q_glossy,ret_img/https://www.offisia.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/09/qn2.png '''QN Tower''' (QIII)]\n|[[Larnaca]]\n|53,2m\n|175ft\n|13\n|TBA\n|Approved\n|Commercial\n|<small><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.qualitydevelopments.com/projects/commercial/item/qn-tower?category_id=4|title=QN Tower Quality Property Developments|website=www.qualitydevelopments.com|access-date=2020-02-12}}</ref></small>\n|- style=\"background:#FFB347;\"\n|67\n|[https://static.wixstatic.com/media/56e28a_534d0bdfcb0741d394d07276e9b66672~mv2_d_1474_2030_s_2.jpg/v1/fill/w_300,h_413,al_c,q_80,usm_0.66_1.00_0.01/56e28a_534d0bdfcb0741d394d07276e9b66672~mv2_d_1474_2030_s_2.webp '''The Tower'''] <small>at St. Raphael Resort</small>\n|[[Limassol]]\n|53m\n|174ft\n|13\n|2020\n|Under Construction\n|Residential\n|<small>A residential highrise building within [https://www.straphael.com/ St. Raphael Resort and Marina] grounds. Almost completed<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.thetowerlimassol.com/|title=The Tower Limassol|website=the-tower-limassol|language=en|access-date=2020-01-28}}</ref></small>\n|-\n|- style=\"background: pink;\"\n|68\n|'''[https://i.imgur.com/WAMVfiE.jpg Amathus Residences]'''\n|[[Limassol]]\n|\u224853m\n|\u2248174ft\n|13\n|\n|Proposed\n|Residential\n|<small>A residential highrise building to be erected within [https://www.amathuslimassol.com/ Amathus Beach Hotel] grounds</small>\n|-\n|-\n|-\n|-\n|-\n|-\n|-\n|-\n|-\n|-\n|-\n|-\n|-\n|-\n|}<br />\n\n== Cities with buildings \u226550m (under construction only) ==\nList measures approved and/or buildings under construction by roof height only.\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|+\n!City\n!\u226550m\n|-\n|[[Limassol]]\n|22\n|-\n|[[Nicosia]]\n|5\n|-\n|[[Larnaca]]\n|0\n|-\n|[[Paphos]]\n|0\n|-\n|[[Ayia Napa]]\n|2\n|}<br />\n== Gallery ==\n{{Gallery}}<gallery widths=\"200\" heights=\"200\">\nFile:Nicosia Shacolas Tower.jpg|[[Shacolas Tower]]\nFile:Limassol 01-2017 img02 Olympic Residence.jpg|Olympic Residence\nFile:Leventis Gallery Makariou Avenue Nicosia Cyprus.jpg|[[Leventis Gallery]]\nFile:Limassol 01-2017 img10 TheOval.jpg|[[The Oval (Limassol)|The Oval]]\nFile:President Building, Nicosia.jpg|The President, Nicosia\nFile:Nicosia 01-2017 img16 View from Shacolas Tower.jpg|[[Tower 25]] \n</gallery>{{Gallery|title=}}\n\n== See also == \n*[[List of tallest buildings in the European Union]]\n*[[List of tallest buildings in Europe]]\n*[[List of tallest buildings|List of tallest buildings in the world]]\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n[[Category:Lists of buildings and structures in Cyprus]]\n[[Category:Lists of tallest buildings in Europe|Cyprus]]\n[[Category:Skyscrapers in Cyprus]]\n[[Category:Lists of tallest structures by country|Cyprus]]\n\n{{TBSW}}\n", "name_user": "Loucozade", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eBuildings under construction", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/List_of_tallest_buildings_in_Cyprus"}
{"title_page": "Spike Island (Cheshire)", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=November 2019}}\n[[Image:Spike Island.jpg|thumb|260px|Spike Island from Catalyst]]\n'''Spike Island''' is an island between the [[Sankey Canal]]<ref name=\"sankey\" /> and the estuary of the [[River Mersey]], part of [[Widnes]] in the borough of [[Halton (borough)|Halton]] in north-west England. The island contains parkland, woodland, a path along the canal and is next to the [[Catalyst Science Discovery Centre]], the only science museum in the UK solely devoted to chemistry.\n\n==History==\nThe island was at the centre of the British [[chemical industry]] during the 19th century and part of the [[Industrial Revolution]]. However, by the 1970s the area contained abandoned chemical factories, rail lines, canal and industrial dockage, and extensive chemical [[pollution]]. Between 1975 and 1982 the island was reclaimed and returned to green spaces.\n\n==In popular culture==\nSpike Island was the site of a [[Spike Island (concert)|famous outdoor concert]] by [[The Stone Roses]] in May 1990;<ref name=\"BBCvideo\" /> the support acts included [[Disc jockey|DJ]]s [[Dave Haslam]], [[Paul Oakenfold]] and [[Frankie Bones]], a [[Zimbabwe]]an [[drum]] [[orchestra]], Dave Booth (DJ) and the [[reggae]] artist [[Gary Clail]].<ref name=\"nme\" /> A film about the concert called ''[[Spike Island (film)|Spike Island]]'' was released in 2012.<ref name=\"liverpoolecho\" />\n\n==References==\n{{Portal|Cheshire}}\n{{reflist|refs=\n<ref name=\"sankey\">{{cite web |url=http://www.penninewaterways.co.uk/sankey/sa49.htm |title=Spike Island and Widnes Lock - Sankey Canal |publisher=penninewaterways.co.uk |accessdate=8 March 2013}}</ref>\n<ref name=\"BBCvideo\">{{cite web | url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/music/sevenages/events/indie/stone-roses-at-spike-island/ | title=BBC Short film on the Stone Roses Spike Island concert | publisher=BBC}}</ref>\n<ref name=\"liverpoolecho\">{{cite news|last=Wright |first=Jade |url=http://www.liverpoolecho.co.uk/liverpool-entertainment/echo-entertainment/2012/03/26/new-film-to-relive-the-stone-roses-classic-gig-at-spike-island-in-widnes-100252-30622394/ |title=New film to relive The Stone Roses\u2019 classic gig at Spike Island in Widnes |newspaper=[[Liverpool Echo]] |date=26 March 2012 |accessdate=31 March 2012}}</ref>\n<ref name=\"nme\">{{cite news|last=Nicolson|first=Barry|url=http://www.nme.com/features/the-stone-roses-the-full-story-of-spike-island-25-years-on|title=The Stone Roses: The Full Story Of Spike Island, 25 Years On|newspaper=nme |date=27 May 2015 |accessdate=27 May 2015}}</ref>\n}}\n\n{{coord |53|21|14|N|2|43|50|W|type:isle_region:GB-HAL|display=title}}\n\n[[Category:Landforms of Cheshire]]\n[[Category:Islands of England]]\n[[Category:Widnes]]\n[[Category:River Mersey]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=November 2019}}\n[[Image:Spike Island.jpg|thumb|260px|Spike Island from Catalyst]]\n'''Spike Island''' is an [[island]] between the [[Sankey Canal]]<ref name=\"sankey\" /> and the estuary of the [[River Mersey]], part of [[Widnes]] in the borough of [[Halton (borough)|Halton]] in north-west England. The island contains parkland, woodland, a path along the canal and is next to the [[Catalyst Science Discovery Centre]], the only science museum in the UK solely devoted to chemistry.\n\n==History==\nThe island was at the centre of the British [[chemical industry]] during the 19th century and part of the [[Industrial Revolution]]. However, by the 1970s the area contained abandoned chemical factories, rail lines, canal and industrial dockage, and extensive chemical [[pollution]]. Between 1975 and 1982 the island was reclaimed and returned to green spaces.\n\n==In popular culture==\nSpike Island was the site of a [[Spike Island (concert)|famous outdoor concert]] by [[The Stone Roses]] in May 1990;<ref name=\"BBCvideo\" /> the support acts included [[Disc jockey|DJ]]s [[Dave Haslam]], [[Paul Oakenfold]] and [[Frankie Bones]], a [[Zimbabwe]]an [[drum]] [[orchestra]], Dave Booth (DJ) and the [[reggae]] artist [[Gary Clail]].<ref name=\"nme\" /> A film about the concert called ''[[Spike Island (film)|Spike Island]]'' was released in 2012.<ref name=\"liverpoolecho\" />\n\n==References==\n{{Portal|Cheshire}}\n{{reflist|refs=\n<ref name=\"sankey\">{{cite web |url=http://www.penninewaterways.co.uk/sankey/sa49.htm |title=Spike Island and Widnes Lock - Sankey Canal |publisher=penninewaterways.co.uk |accessdate=8 March 2013}}</ref>\n<ref name=\"BBCvideo\">{{cite web | url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/music/sevenages/events/indie/stone-roses-at-spike-island/ | title=BBC Short film on the Stone Roses Spike Island concert | publisher=BBC}}</ref>\n<ref name=\"liverpoolecho\">{{cite news|last=Wright |first=Jade |url=http://www.liverpoolecho.co.uk/liverpool-entertainment/echo-entertainment/2012/03/26/new-film-to-relive-the-stone-roses-classic-gig-at-spike-island-in-widnes-100252-30622394/ |title=New film to relive The Stone Roses\u2019 classic gig at Spike Island in Widnes |newspaper=[[Liverpool Echo]] |date=26 March 2012 |accessdate=31 March 2012}}</ref>\n<ref name=\"nme\">{{cite news|last=Nicolson|first=Barry|url=http://www.nme.com/features/the-stone-roses-the-full-story-of-spike-island-25-years-on|title=The Stone Roses: The Full Story Of Spike Island, 25 Years On|newspaper=nme |date=27 May 2015 |accessdate=27 May 2015}}</ref>\n}}\n\n{{coord |53|21|14|N|2|43|50|W|type:isle_region:GB-HAL|display=title}}\n\n[[Category:Landforms of Cheshire]]\n[[Category:Islands of England]]\n[[Category:Borough of Halton]]\n[[Category:Widnes]]\n[[Category:River Mersey]]\n", "name_user": "Crouch, Swale", "label": "safe", "comment": "redundant category", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Spike_Island_(Cheshire)"}
{"title_page": "Karl Carstens", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2020}}\n{{Infobox President \n| name          = Karl Carstens\n| image         = Bundesarchiv B 145 Bild-F054633-0020, Ludwigshafen, CDU-Bundesparteitag, Carstens (cropped).jpg\n| width         = 218px\n| order         =\n\n| office        = [[President of Germany]]<br /><small>([[West Germany]])</small>\n| term_start    = 1 July 1979\n| term_end      = 30 June 1984\n| chancellor    = [[Helmut Schmidt]] <br/>[[Helmut Kohl]]\n| predecessor   = [[Walter Scheel]]\n| successor     = [[Richard von Weizs\u00e4cker]]\n\n| office1       = [[President of the Bundestag]]<br /><small>([[West Germany]])</small>\n| term_start1   = 14 December 1976 \t\n| term_end1     = 31 May 1979\n| predecessor1  = [[Annemarie Renger]]\n| successor1    = [[Richard St\u00fccklen]]\n\n| office2       = Bundestag Leader of the [[CDU/CSU|CDU/CSU Group]]\n| term_start2   = 17 May 1973 \t\n| term_end2     = 1 December 1976\n| predecessor2  = [[Kurt Georg Kiesinger]] <small>(acting)</small>\n| successor2    = [[Helmut Kohl]]\n\n| office3        = [[Chiefs of the Federal Chancellery|Chief of the Federal Chancellery]]<br /><small>([[West Germany]])</small>\n| term_start3    = 1 January 1968\n| term_end3      = 22 October 1969\n| chancellor3    = [[Kurt Georg Kiesinger]]\n| predecessor3   = Werner Knieper\n| successor3     = [[Horst Ehmke]]\n\n| office4        = Member of the [[Bundestag]] <br /> for [[Ostholstein]]\n| term_start4    = 3 October 1976\n| term_end4      = 1 July 1979\n| predecessor4   = Constituency established\n| successor4     = G\u00fcnther Jansen\n\n| office5        = Member of the [[Bundestag]] <br /> for [[Schleswig-Holstein]]\n| term_start5    = 19 November 1972\n| term_end5      = 3 October 1976\n| constituency5 = <!-- [[Electoral system of Germany]] -->\n\n| birth_date    = {{Birth date|1914|12|14|df=y}}\n| birth_place   = [[Bremen]], [[German Empire]]\n| death_date    = {{Death date and age|1992|05|30|1914|12|14|df=y}}\n| death_place   = [[Meckenheim (Rhineland)|Meckenheim]], [[Germany]]\n| spouse        = [[Veronica Carstens|Veronica Prior]]\n| party         = [[Christian Democratic Union (Germany)|Christian Democratic Union]] <small>(1955\u20131992)</small>\n| otherparty    = [[Nazi Party]] <small>(1940\u20131945)</small>\n| nationality   = [[Germany|German]]\n}}\n'''Karl Carstens''' (14 December 1914 \u2013 30 May 1992) was a German politician. He served as [[President of Germany|President of the Federal Republic of Germany]] ([[West Germany]]) from 1979 to 1984.\n\n==Early life and education==\nCarstens was born in the City of [[Bremen]], the son of a commercial school teacher, who had been killed at the [[Western Front (World War I)|Western Front]] of [[World War I]] shortly before his birth. He studied law and political science at the universities of [[Goethe University Frankfurt|Frankfurt]], [[University of Burgundy|Dijon]], [[Ludwig Maximilian University of Munich|Munich]], [[University of K\u00f6nigsberg|K\u00f6nigsberg]], and [[University of Hamburg|Hamburg]] from 1933 to 1936, gaining a [[Doctor (title)|doctorate]] in 1938 and taking the Second ''[[Staatsexamen]]'' degree in 1939. In 1949 he also received a [[Master of Laws]] ([[LL.M.]]) degree from [[Yale Law School]].\n\n==World War II==\n[[File:Bundesarchiv Bild 146-2008-0320, Karl Carstens, Veronica Carstens.jpg|thumb|right|Karl and Veronica Carstens in 1949]]\nFrom 1939 to 1945, during the [[Second World War]], Carstens was a member of an [[Anti-aircraft warfare|anti-aircraft artillery]] (''Flak'') unit in the [[Luftwaffe (Wehrmacht)|Luftwaffe]], reaching the rank of ''[[Leutnant]]'' (Second Lieutenant) by the war's end. In 1940 he joined the [[Nazi Party]]; reportedly, he had applied for admission in 1937 to avoid detrimental treatment when he worked as a [[law clerk]]. He had, however, joined the Nazi ''[[Sturmabteilung|SA]]'' paramilitary organisation already in 1934.\n\n==Post-war years==\nIn 1944 Carstens married the medical student [[Veronica Carstens|Veronica Prior]] in [[Berlin]]. After the war he became a [[lawyer]] in his hometown Bremen, and from 1949 acted as a councillor of the [[Senate of Bremen|city's Senate]]. From 1950 he also worked as lecturer at the [[University of Cologne]], where he habilitated two years later. In 1954 he joined the diplomatic service of the German [[Foreign Office (Germany)|Foreign Office]], serving as [[West Germany|West German]] representative at the [[Council of Europe]] in [[Strasbourg]]. In 1955 he joined the [[Christian Democratic Union (Germany)|Christian Democratic Union]] (CDU) under Chancellor [[Konrad Adenauer]].\n\nIn July 1960 Carstens reached the position of [[secretary of state]] at the Foreign Office and in the same year was also appointed as professor for public and international law at Cologne University. During the [[Grand coalition (Germany)|grand coalition]] government of 1966-1969 under Chancellor [[Kurt Georg Kiesinger]], he first served as secretary of state in the [[Federal Ministry of Defence (Germany)|Ministry of Defence]], and after 1968 as head of the [[German Chancellery]].\n\nIn [[1972 West German federal election|1972]] Carstens was first elected into the [[Bundestag]], of which he was a member until 1979. From May 1973 until October 1976 he was chairman of the CDU/[[Christian Social Union of Bavaria|CSU]] parliamentary group, succeeding [[Rainer Barzel]]. During that time he was an outspoken critic of left-wing tendencies in the [[German student movement]] and particular accused the governing [[Social Democratic Party of Germany]] (SPD) of being too soft on left-wing extremists. He also famously denounced the author and [[Nobel Prize in Literature|Nobel]] laureate [[Heinrich B\u00f6ll]] as a supporter of [[left-wing terrorism]] (specifically, the [[Red Army Faction|Baader-Meinhof Gang]]) for his 1974 novel ''[[The Lost Honour of Katharina Blum]]''.\n\nAfter the [[1976 West German federal election|1976 federal elections]], which made the CDU/CSU the largest group in parliament, Carstens was elected president of the Bundestag on 14 December 1976. The CDU/CSU had also reached a majority in the [[Federal Convention (Germany)|Federal Convention]] electing the [[President of Germany]], and in 1979 the party nominated Carstens, though in contestation due to his Nazi past, as candidate, whereafter incumbent President [[Walter Scheel]] ([[Free Democratic Party (Germany)|FDP]]) chose to renounce a second term.\n\n==President of West Germany==\n[[File:Bundesarchiv B 145 Bild-F057221-0004, Wanderung des Bundespr\u00e4sidenten Carstens.jpg|thumb|right|The hiking president, 1979]]\nOn 23 May 1979, Carstens was elected as the fifth President of the Federal Republic of Germany, prevailing against the SPD candidate [[Annemarie Renger]] in the first ballot. During his term of office, Carstens was well known for [[hiking]] Germany in order to decrease the gulf between politics and the people.\n\nIn December 1982, the new Chancellor [[Helmut Kohl]] (CDU), recently elected in a successful [[motion of no confidence]] against [[Helmut Schmidt]] (SPD) deliberately lost a vote of confidence in the Bundestag, in order to obtain a clearer majority in new general elections. Though already former Chancellor [[Willy Brandt]] had similarly proceeded in 1972, this action gave rise to a discussion whether such a step constitutes a \"manipulation of the [[Basic Law for the Federal Republic of Germany|Constitution]]\". On 7 January 1983, President Carstens nonetheless dissolved the Bundestag and called for new elections. In February 1983 his decision was approved by the [[Federal Constitutional Court of Germany|Federal Constitutional Court]] so that [[1983 West German federal election|1983 general elections]] could take place on 6 March.\n\nIn 1984 Carstens decided not to seek a second term on account of his age and left office on 30 June 1984. He was succeeded by [[Richard von Weizs\u00e4cker]].\n\nCarstens was a member of the [[Evangelical Church in Germany]].\n\n==Literature==\n* [[Michael F. Feldkamp]] (ed.), ''Der [[President of the Bundestag|Bundestagspr\u00e4sident]]. Amt - Funktion - Person.'' 16. Wahlperiode, M\u00fcnchen 2007, {{ISBN|978-3-7892-8201-0}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://archives.eui.eu/en/oral_history/INT494 Interview] with Karl Carstens at [http://www.eui.eu/Research/HistoricalArchivesOfEU/Index.aspx Historical Archives of the EU] in Florence\n\n{{commons|Karl Carstens}}\n\n{{S-start}}\n{{s-off}}\n{{Succession box|\n  title=[[President of Germany|President of West Germany]]|\n  before=[[Walter Scheel]]|\n  after=[[Richard von Weizs\u00e4cker]]|\n  years=1979&ndash;1984\n}}\n{{Succession box|\n  title=[[President of the Bundestag]]|\n  before=[[Annemarie Renger]]|\n  after=[[Richard St\u00fccklen]]|\n  years=1976&ndash;1979\n}}\n{{S-end}}\n\n{{German presidents}}\n{{BundestagPresidents}}\n{{CDU/CSU chairmen}}\n{{Heads of the German Chancellery}}\n{{Charlemagne Prize recipients}}\n{{CDU/CSU presidential candidates}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Carstens, Karl}}\n[[Category:1914 births]]\n[[Category:1992 deaths]]\n[[Category:20th-century Presidents of Germany]]\n[[Category:People from Bremen]]\n[[Category:Presidents of Germany]]\n[[Category:German military personnel of World War II]]\n[[Category:German Lutherans]]\n[[Category:Christian Democratic Union of Germany politicians]]\n[[Category:Presidents of the Bundestag]]\n[[Category:Yale Law School alumni]]\n[[Category:German scholars of constitutional law]]\n[[Category:Recipients of the Grand Star of the Decoration for Services to the Republic of Austria]]\n[[Category:Recipients of the Bavarian Order of Merit]]\n[[Category:Heads of the German Chancellery]]\n[[Category:Grand Crosses Special Class of the Order of Merit of the Federal Republic of Germany]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox President \n| name          = Karl Carstens\n| image         = Bundesarchiv B 145 Bild-F054633-0020, Ludwigshafen, CDU-Bundesparteitag, Carstens (cropped).jpg\n| width         = 218px\n| order         =\n\n| office        = [[President of Germany]]<br /><small>([[West Germany]])</small>\n| term_start    = 1 July 1979\n| term_end      = 30 June 1984\n| chancellor    = [[Helmut Schmidt]] <br/>[[Helmut Kohl]]\n| predecessor   = [[Walter Scheel]]\n| successor     = [[Richard von Weizs\u00e4cker]]\n\n| office1       = [[President of the Bundestag]]<br /><small>([[West Germany]])</small>\n| term_start1   = 14 December 1976 \t\n| term_end1     = 31 May 1979\n| predecessor1  = [[Annemarie Renger]]\n| successor1    = [[Richard St\u00fccklen]]\n\n| office2       = Bundestag Leader of the [[CDU/CSU|CDU/CSU Group]]\n| term_start2   = 17 May 1973 \t\n| term_end2     = 1 December 1976\n| predecessor2  = [[Kurt Georg Kiesinger]] <small>(acting)</small>\n| successor2    = [[Helmut Kohl]]\n\n| office3        = [[Chiefs of the Federal Chancellery|Chief of the Federal Chancellery]]<br /><small>([[West Germany]])</small>\n| term_start3    = 1 January 1968\n| term_end3      = 22 October 1969\n| chancellor3    = [[Kurt Georg Kiesinger]]\n| predecessor3   = Werner Knieper\n| successor3     = [[Horst Ehmke]]\n\n| office4        = Member of the [[Bundestag]] <br /> for [[Ostholstein]]\n| term_start4    = 3 October 1976\n| term_end4      = 1 July 1979\n| predecessor4   = Constituency established\n| successor4     = G\u00fcnther Jansen\n\n| office5        = Member of the [[Bundestag]] <br /> for [[Schleswig-Holstein]]\n| term_start5    = 19 November 1972\n| term_end5      = 3 October 1976\n| constituency5 = <!-- [[Electoral system of Germany]] -->\n\n| birth_date    = {{Birth date|1914|12|14|df=y}}\n| birth_place   = [[Bremen]], [[German Empire]]\n| death_date    = {{Death date and age|1992|05|30|1914|12|14|df=y}}\n| death_place   = [[Meckenheim (Rhineland)|Meckenheim]], [[Germany]]\n| spouse        = [[Veronica Carstens|Veronica Prior]]\n| party         = [[Christian Democratic Union (Germany)|Christian Democratic Union]] <small>(1955\u20131992)</small>\n| otherparty    = [[Nazi Party]] <small>(1940\u20131945)</small>\n| nationality   = [[Germany|German]]\n}}\n'''Karl Carstens''' (14 December 1914 \u2013 30 May 1992) was a [[Germany|German]] politician. He served as [[President of Germany|President of the Federal Republic of Germany]] ([[West Germany]]) from 1979 to 1984.\n\n==Early life and education==\nCarstens was born in the City of [[Bremen]], the son of a commercial school teacher, who had been killed at the [[Western Front (World War I)|Western Front]] of [[World War I]] shortly before his birth. He studied law and political science at the universities of [[Goethe University Frankfurt|Frankfurt]], [[University of Burgundy|Dijon]], [[Ludwig Maximilian University of Munich|Munich]], [[University of K\u00f6nigsberg|K\u00f6nigsberg]], and [[University of Hamburg|Hamburg]] from 1933 to 1936, gaining a [[Doctor (title)|doctorate]] in 1938 and taking the Second ''[[Staatsexamen]]'' degree in 1939. In 1949 he also received a [[Master of Laws]] ([[LL.M.]]) degree from [[Yale Law School]].\n\n==World War II==\n[[File:Bundesarchiv Bild 146-2008-0320, Karl Carstens, Veronica Carstens.jpg|thumb|right|Karl and Veronica Carstens in 1949]]\nFrom 1939 to 1945, during the [[Second World War]], Carstens was a member of an [[Anti-aircraft warfare|anti-aircraft artillery]] (''Flak'') unit in the [[Luftwaffe (Wehrmacht)|Luftwaffe]], reaching the rank of ''[[Leutnant]]'' (Second Lieutenant) by the war's end. In 1940 he joined the [[Nazi Party]]; reportedly, he had applied for admission in 1937 to avoid detrimental treatment when he worked as a [[law clerk]]. He had, however, joined the Nazi ''[[Sturmabteilung|SA]]'' paramilitary organisation already in 1934.\n\n==Post-war years==\nIn 1944 Carstens married the medical student [[Veronica Carstens|Veronica Prior]] in [[Berlin]]. After the war he became a [[lawyer]] in his hometown Bremen, and from 1949 acted as a councillor of the [[Senate of Bremen|city's Senate]]. From 1950 he also worked as lecturer at the [[University of Cologne]], where he habilitated two years later. In 1954 he joined the diplomatic service of the German [[Foreign Office (Germany)|Foreign Office]], serving as [[West Germany|West German]] representative at the [[Council of Europe]] in [[Strasbourg]]. In 1955 he joined the [[Christian Democratic Union (Germany)|Christian Democratic Union]] (CDU) under Chancellor [[Konrad Adenauer]].\n\nIn July 1960 Carstens reached the position of [[secretary of state]] at the Foreign Office and in the same year was also appointed as professor for public and international law at Cologne University. During the [[Grand coalition (Germany)|grand coalition]] government of 1966-1969 under Chancellor [[Kurt Georg Kiesinger]], he first served as secretary of state in the [[Federal Ministry of Defence (Germany)|Ministry of Defence]], and after 1968 as head of the [[German Chancellery]].\n\nIn [[1972 West German federal election|1972]] Carstens was first elected into the [[Bundestag]], of which he was a member until 1979. From May 1973 until October 1976 he was chairman of the CDU/[[Christian Social Union of Bavaria|CSU]] parliamentary group, succeeding [[Rainer Barzel]]. During that time he was an outspoken critic of left-wing tendencies in the [[German student movement]] and particular accused the governing [[Social Democratic Party of Germany]] (SPD) of being too soft on left-wing extremists. He also famously denounced the author and [[Nobel Prize in Literature|Nobel]] laureate [[Heinrich B\u00f6ll]] as a supporter of [[left-wing terrorism]] (specifically, the [[Red Army Faction|Baader-Meinhof Gang]]) for his 1974 novel ''[[The Lost Honour of Katharina Blum]]''.\n\nAfter the [[1976 West German federal election|1976 federal elections]], which made the CDU/CSU the largest group in parliament, Carstens was elected president of the Bundestag on 14 December 1976. The CDU/CSU had also reached a majority in the [[Federal Convention (Germany)|Federal Convention]] electing the [[President of Germany]], and in 1979 the party nominated Carstens, though in contestation due to his Nazi past, as candidate, whereafter incumbent President [[Walter Scheel]] ([[Free Democratic Party (Germany)|FDP]]) chose to renounce a second term.\n\n==President of West Germany==\n[[File:Bundesarchiv B 145 Bild-F057221-0004, Wanderung des Bundespr\u00e4sidenten Carstens.jpg|thumb|right|The hiking president, 1979]]\nOn 23 May 1979, Carstens was elected as the fifth President of the Federal Republic of Germany, prevailing against the SPD candidate [[Annemarie Renger]] in the first ballot. During his term of office, Carstens was well known for [[hiking]] Germany in order to decrease the gulf between politics and the people.\n\nIn December 1982, the new Chancellor [[Helmut Kohl]] (CDU), recently elected in a successful [[motion of no confidence]] against [[Helmut Schmidt]] (SPD) deliberately lost a vote of confidence in the Bundestag, in order to obtain a clearer majority in new general elections. Though already former Chancellor [[Willy Brandt]] had similarly proceeded in 1972, this action gave rise to a discussion whether such a step constitutes a \"manipulation of the [[Basic Law for the Federal Republic of Germany|Constitution]]\". On 7 January 1983, President Carstens nonetheless dissolved the Bundestag and called for new elections. In February 1983 his decision was approved by the [[Federal Constitutional Court of Germany|Federal Constitutional Court]] so that [[1983 West German federal election|1983 general elections]] could take place on 6 March.\n\nIn 1984 Carstens decided not to seek a second term on account of his age and left office on 30 June 1984. He was succeeded by [[Richard von Weizs\u00e4cker]].\n\nCarstens was a member of the [[Evangelical Church in Germany]].\n\n==Literature==\n* [[Michael F. Feldkamp]] (ed.), ''Der [[President of the Bundestag|Bundestagspr\u00e4sident]]. Amt - Funktion - Person.'' 16. Wahlperiode, M\u00fcnchen 2007, {{ISBN|978-3-7892-8201-0}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://archives.eui.eu/en/oral_history/INT494 Interview] with Karl Carstens at [http://www.eui.eu/Research/HistoricalArchivesOfEU/Index.aspx Historical Archives of the EU] in Florence\n\n{{commons|Karl Carstens}}\n\n{{S-start}}\n{{s-off}}\n{{Succession box|\n  title=[[President of Germany|President of West Germany]]|\n  before=[[Walter Scheel]]|\n  after=[[Richard von Weizs\u00e4cker]]|\n  years=1979&ndash;1984\n}}\n{{Succession box|\n  title=[[President of the Bundestag]]|\n  before=[[Annemarie Renger]]|\n  after=[[Richard St\u00fccklen]]|\n  years=1976&ndash;1979\n}}\n{{S-end}}\n\n{{German presidents}}\n{{BundestagPresidents}}\n{{CDU/CSU chairmen}}\n{{Heads of the German Chancellery}}\n{{Charlemagne Prize recipients}}\n{{CDU/CSU presidential candidates}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Carstens, Karl}}\n[[Category:1914 births]]\n[[Category:1992 deaths]]\n[[Category:20th-century Presidents of Germany]]\n[[Category:People from Bremen]]\n[[Category:Presidents of Germany]]\n[[Category:German military personnel of World War II]]\n[[Category:German Lutherans]]\n[[Category:Christian Democratic Union of Germany politicians]]\n[[Category:Presidents of the Bundestag]]\n[[Category:Yale Law School alumni]]\n[[Category:German scholars of constitutional law]]\n[[Category:Recipients of the Grand Star of the Decoration for Services to the Republic of Austria]]\n[[Category:Recipients of the Bavarian Order of Merit]]\n[[Category:Heads of the German Chancellery]]\n[[Category:Grand Crosses Special Class of the Order of Merit of the Federal Republic of Germany]]\n", "name_user": "Robby.is.on", "label": "safe", "comment": "Fix overlinking.", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Karl_Carstens"}
